"""
Context Layer — Ezra chapters 1–3
Run: python3 scripts/zc-context-ezra-1-3.py

Ch 1 v1 already exists; vv 2-11 are new.
Ch 2 (70 verses) and Ch 3 (13 verses) are fully new.

Key historical/ANE background:
- Ch 1: The Cyrus Cylinder (538 BCE) confirms Persian policy of returning gods/peoples to
  homelands; Cyrus's decree in Aramaic royal-letter format; inventory of 5,400 temple vessels
- Ch 2: Parallel to Neh 7:6-73 (same list); Persian medinah administrative terminology;
  priestly lineage crisis (Urim and Thummim as oracle); Nethinim as non-Israelite temple
  servants; relatively few Levites (74 vs. 4,289 priests) — Levitical reluctance to return
- Ch 3: Altar before temple (cf. Haggai's critique of priorities); Feast of Tabernacles first
  celebration; Solomonic building pattern (Tyrian/Sidonian craftsmen); mixed response of
  joy and weeping at foundation-laying — Haggai/Zechariah address this ambiguity
"""

import json, pathlib

ROOT = pathlib.Path(__file__).parent.parent

def load_comm(source, book):
    p = ROOT / 'data' / 'commentary' / source / f'{book}.json'
    if p.exists():
        return json.loads(p.read_text())
    return {}

def save_comm(source, book, data):
    p = ROOT / 'data' / 'commentary' / source / f'{book}.json'
    p.parent.mkdir(parents=True, exist_ok=True)
    p.write_text(json.dumps(data, ensure_ascii=False, indent=None))
    print(f'  wrote {p.relative_to(ROOT)}')

def merge_comm(existing, new_data):
    for ch, verses in new_data.items():
        if ch not in existing:
            existing[ch] = {}
        for v, html in verses.items():
            if v not in existing[ch]:
                existing[ch][v] = html

EZRA_CONTEXT_1_3 = {
  "1": {
    "2": "<p>Cyrus&rsquo;s declaration — &ldquo;YHWH the God of heaven has given me all the kingdoms of the earth, and he has charged me to build him a house at Jerusalem&rdquo; — is a royal Aramaic edict in the standard Persian proclamation format. The Cyrus Cylinder (British Museum, 539 BCE) independently confirms that Cyrus adopted the policy of restoring gods, cult images, and deported peoples to their homelands as a deliberate act of imperial self-legitimation. The Cylinder says Cyrus was commissioned by Marduk to restore the Babylonian sanctuaries; Ezra 1:2 presents the same act of restoration as commissioned by YHWH. Cyrus apparently adapted his proclamation to each audience — the Babylonians heard of Marduk&rsquo;s commission; the Jews heard of YHWH&rsquo;s. Isaiah had named Cyrus explicitly as YHWH&rsquo;s agent (Isa 44:28; 45:1) over 150 years before this decree.</p>",
    "3": "<p>&ldquo;Whoever is among you of all his people, may his God be with him, and let him go up to Jerusalem&rdquo; — the voluntary character of the return is significant. The Cyrus edict did not command the exile community to leave; it permitted and encouraged those who wished to return. The majority of Babylonian Jews remained in Babylon (the Babylonian Jewish community continued for over a millennium). The phrase &ldquo;let him go up&rdquo; (<em>weya&lsquo;al</em>) uses the technical pilgrimage verb for ascending to Jerusalem; the return is framed as a sacred pilgrimage to rebuild, not merely an administrative transfer.</p>",
    "4": "<p>&ldquo;And let each survivor, in whatever place he sojourns, be assisted by the men of his place with silver and gold, with goods and with beasts, besides freewill offerings for the house of God&rdquo; — two types of support are called for: (1) practical support from non-returning neighbors (parallel to the Exodus pattern, where Egypt&rsquo;s silver and gold equipped the departing Israelites, Exod 12:35-36); and (2) voluntary temple donations. The dual appeal — material support and voluntary sacred giving — reflects the community organization of the Persian-period Jewish diaspora, which supported both those who returned and those who stayed.</p>",
    "5": "<p>Those who &ldquo;stirred up&rdquo; (<em>he&lsquo;îr</em>) to go up are the heads of the fathers&rsquo; houses of Judah and Benjamin, plus the priests and Levites. The same verb as v1 (&ldquo;the LORD stirred up the spirit of Cyrus&rdquo;) — divine stirring operates at the political level (the king) and the communal level (individual families). Judah and Benjamin represent the southern kingdom that went into Babylonian exile; the northern tribes were exiled to Assyria in 722 BCE and are largely absent from this narrative. The post-exilic community sees itself as the continuation of the Davidic kingdom.</p>",
    "6": "<p>&ldquo;All their neighbors aided them with vessels of silver, with gold, with goods, with beasts, and with costly wares, besides all that was freely offered&rdquo; — the Exodus typology is deliberate: just as Israel &ldquo;plundered the Egyptians&rdquo; (Exod 12:36), the returning exiles receive material support from their Babylonian neighbors. The prophets had promised that the restoration would outdo the Exodus (Isa 43:16-21; 52:11-12). The voluntary character of the Gentile neighbors&rsquo; gifts also echoes the freewill offerings for the tabernacle (Exod 35:20-29).</p>",
    "7": "<p>Cyrus brings out the vessels of the house of YHWH that Nebuchadnezzar had carried away — the return of the temple vessels is the most concrete sign of restoration. In ANE thought, a god&rsquo;s power was linked to the cult objects housed in his temple; when Nebuchadnezzar took the vessels to Babylon and placed them in the treasury of his gods (Dan 1:2; 2 Chr 36:18), it was a theological statement that YHWH had been defeated. Their return under Cyrus reverses that statement. The vessels are in effect YHWH&rsquo;s returning &ldquo;presence&rdquo; before the temple is rebuilt.</p>",
    "8": "<p>Sheshbazzar the prince of Judah receives the vessels — he is identified in Ezra 5:14-16 as the one who laid the temple foundations. &ldquo;Prince&rdquo; (<em>nāśîʾ</em>) is a title associated with the Davidic line in Ezekiel&rsquo;s restoration vision (Ezek 34:24; 37:25). Sheshbazzar is possibly the Shenazzar of 1 Chr 3:18, son of Jehoiachin — a member of the exiled Davidic royal family. His role as the official receiver of the vessels on behalf of Judah gives the return an explicitly Davidic character from the outset.</p>",
    "9": "<p>The inventory begins: 30 gold dishes, 1,000 silver dishes, 29 censers — the beginning of a detailed accounting that reflects the meticulous record-keeping of the Persian imperial administration. Temple treasuries throughout the ancient world maintained detailed inventories of their holdings; the return of items from one imperial archive to another required comprehensive documentation. Ezra preserves this official inventory, giving the restoration a bureaucratically verified character.</p>",
    "10": "<p>Gold bowls (30), duplicate silver bowls (410), other vessels (1,000) — the continuation of the inventory. The precision of the numbers indicates use of actual temple archives or Persian administrative records. The three-level categorization (gold / silver / other) reflects ANE temple treasury classification. The detailed enumeration makes a theological point: nothing was lost. YHWH&rsquo;s temple treasure was preserved through the exile and is now fully restored.</p>",
    "11": "<p>Total: 5,400 gold and silver vessels. The number signals comprehensiveness — the restored temple begins with a fully equipped treasury rather than starting from nothing. The phrase &ldquo;all these did Sheshbazzar bring up, when the exiles were brought up from Babylon to Jerusalem&rdquo; formally closes the vessel-return narrative and links the physical return of the sacred objects with the community&rsquo;s return — the people and the temple implements travel together, as when the ark led Israel&rsquo;s march (Num 10:33-36).</p>"
  },
  "2": {
    "1": "<p>The heading of the census identifies the returnees as &ldquo;the province&rdquo; (<em>hammedînāh</em>) — Persian administrative terminology designating Judah as a sub-province of the satrapy &ldquo;Beyond the River&rdquo; (Eber-nari, the territory west of the Euphrates). Babylon was the metropolitan center; Judah was a minor administrative unit. The parallel list in Neh 7:6-73 is nearly identical, suggesting both texts draw on the same official registry maintained by the Persian administration. The returnees are defined not as those who left Babylon but as those &ldquo;whom Nebuchadnezzar had carried away&rdquo; — the exile is the defining historical moment from which the community&rsquo;s identity is reckoned.</p>",
    "2": "<p>Zerubbabel heads the list of eleven leaders (twelve if Nehemiah and Azariah are counted separately). Zerubbabel ben Shealtiel is a Davidic descendant (1 Chr 3:17-19); Jeshua ben Jozadak is the high priest (Hag 1:1). This dual leadership (Davidic prince + priestly leader) is the organizational structure of the restored community and the basis for Zechariah&rsquo;s vision of the two olive trees (Zech 4:11-14). The other names include Nehemiah (not the wall-builder), Mordecai (not the Esther figure), and Bigvai — suggesting these were prominent families whose names became leader-designations.</p>",
    "3": "<p>&ldquo;The people of Parosh&rdquo; — 2,172 persons. The pattern &ldquo;people of [family name]&rdquo; (<em>bene + personal name</em>) designates lay families counted by patrilineal descent. Parosh means &ldquo;flea&rdquo; — a common Semitic personal name with no negative connotation in antiquity. The large number (2,172) indicates Parosh was one of the most prominent founding families; the same family appears in the later community (Ezra 8:3; 10:25; Neh 3:25; 7:8).</p>",
    "4": "<p>&ldquo;The people of Shephatiah&rdquo; — 372 persons. Shephatiah (&ldquo;YHWH has judged&rdquo;) is a Judahite/Benjaminite name. The significantly smaller number compared to Parosh (372 vs. 2,172) reflects the natural variation in family size and the differential attrition of exile. These numbers are not symbolic (unlike some census figures in Numbers) but appear to represent administrative counts from actual Persian records.</p>",
    "5": "<p>&ldquo;The people of Arah&rdquo; — 775. Arah (&ldquo;wayfarer&rdquo;) is attested in later biblical texts (Neh 6:18; 7:10 has 652, a textual variant). The family is significant enough that Tobiah the Ammonite adversary of Nehemiah married into it (Neh 6:18), reflecting the social prominence of such founding families in the restored community.</p>",
    "6": "<p>&ldquo;The people of Pahath-moab, of the people of Jeshua and Joab&rdquo; — 2,812. Pahath-moab means &ldquo;governor of Moab&rdquo; — probably an ancestor who had administered the Moabite territory under the Judahite monarchy. This is one of the larger family groups and spans two sub-families (Jeshua and Joab). Their continued prominence is visible in Ezra 8:4; 10:30 and Neh 3:11; 7:11.</p>",
    "7": "<p>&ldquo;The people of Elam&rdquo; — 1,254. Elam was a region east of Babylon (modern southwestern Iran). The family name indicates either an ancestor who had some connection to that region or residence in the Elamite territory during the exile. The same number appears for a second &ldquo;sons of Elam&rdquo; in v31, indicating two distinct families with the same ancestor-name. Together they number 2,508 — making &ldquo;Elam&rdquo; the second-largest family grouping after Parosh.</p>",
    "8": "<p>&ldquo;The people of Zattu&rdquo; — 945. Neh 7:13 has 845, a variant. The presence of textual variants between the Ezra and Nehemiah lists reflects the different sources used: Ezra may draw on the original return registry (538 BCE); Nehemiah may draw on a later administrative census. The differences (ranging from tens to hundreds) indicate independent transmission rather than scribal error in a single copying tradition.</p>",
    "9": "<p>&ldquo;The people of Zaccai&rdquo; — 760. Zaccai (&ldquo;pure&rdquo; or &ldquo;innocent&rdquo;) is also a post-exilic name (Neh 7:14 agrees at 760). The consistency here (unlike Zattu above) suggests this family&rsquo;s number was well-established in the administrative records and transmitted uniformly.</p>",
    "10": "<p>&ldquo;The people of Bani&rdquo; — 642. Neh 7:15 has &ldquo;Binnui&rdquo; with 648. These two variants may represent: (1) the same family known by two slightly different forms of the name; or (2) two separate family heads whose names were confused in transmission. Bani/Binnui appear frequently in the post-exilic community (Ezra 8:10; 10:29, 34, 38; Neh 3:17; 8:7; 10:13, 14).</p>",
    "11": "<p>&ldquo;The people of Bebai&rdquo; — 623. Neh 7:16 has 628. Bebai is a post-exilic family appearing in Ezra 8:11; 10:28 and Neh 7:16; 10:15. The small discrepancy (623 vs. 628) between the Ezra and Nehemiah lists is within the range of scribal variation in large number transmission.</p>",
    "12": "<p>&ldquo;The people of Azgad&rdquo; — 1,222. Neh 7:17 has 2,322 — a very large discrepancy, suggesting either a scribal error (transposition of thousands digit) or that the Nehemiah list draws on a later census reflecting family growth. Azgad appears in Ezra 8:12 and Neh 10:15.</p>",
    "13": "<p>&ldquo;The people of Adonikam&rdquo; — 666. Neh 7:18 has 667. &ldquo;Adonikam&rdquo; means &ldquo;my lord has arisen&rdquo; — a theophoric name with non-YHWH divine element (&ldquo;Adon&rdquo; = Lord), common in pre-exilic Judah. The &ldquo;last ones&rdquo; of Adonikam&rsquo;s sons are mentioned in Ezra 8:13 as late arrivals to a later group of returnees, suggesting this family had members in multiple return waves.</p>",
    "14": "<p>&ldquo;The people of Bigvai&rdquo; — 2,056. Bigvai is a Persian or Aramaic name (&ldquo;happy&rdquo;), suggesting this family head had adopted a Persian name during the exile — a common practice visible throughout the post-exilic community (Daniel = Belteshazzar; Esther = Persian name for Hadassah; Mordecai = Marduk-related name). The large number (2,056) places Bigvai among the top four families.</p>",
    "15": "<p>&ldquo;The people of Adin&rdquo; — 454. Neh 7:20 has 655 — another significant discrepancy. Adin appears in Ezra 8:6 and Neh 10:16. The family name means &ldquo;ornament&rdquo; or &ldquo;delicate.&rdquo;</p>",
    "16": "<p>&ldquo;The people of Ater, namely of Hezekiah&rdquo; — 98. The compound designation &ldquo;people of Ater, of Hezekiah&rdquo; indicates a sub-family or branch: Ater was the ancestor; Hezekiah was a later patriarch who gave the sub-branch its identity. The small number (98) suggests a minor family. The royal name Hezekiah (one of Judah&rsquo;s greatest kings) appearing here reflects the post-exilic community&rsquo;s use of honored historical names for children.</p>",
    "17": "<p>&ldquo;The people of Bezai&rdquo; — 323. Neh 7:23 agrees. Bezai appears in Neh 10:18 as a covenant-signer. The consistency between Ezra and Nehemiah here suggests stable administrative records for this family.</p>",
    "18": "<p>&ldquo;The people of Jorah&rdquo; — 112. Neh 7:24 has &ldquo;Hariph&rdquo; with 112 — same number but different name, suggesting either a family known by two names or a scribal substitution of one similar name for another. Hariph appears in Neh 10:19.</p>",
    "19": "<p>&ldquo;The people of Hashum&rdquo; — 223. Neh 7:22 has 328. Hashum appears in Ezra 10:33 and Neh 8:4; 10:18. The significant numerical discrepancy (223 vs. 328) is unexplained but may reflect different counting methodologies (adult males only vs. entire families).</p>",
    "20": "<p>&ldquo;The people of Gibbar&rdquo; — 95. Neh 7:25 has &ldquo;Gibeon&rdquo; with 95 (same number, different name). Gibeon was a pre-exilic Benjaminite city (Josh 9-10); the substitution of a city name for a personal name in one list versus the other suggests the underlying source sometimes recorded &ldquo;men of [city]&rdquo; and sometimes &ldquo;men of [family patriarch].&rdquo;</p>",
    "21": "<p>&ldquo;The men of Bethlehem&rdquo; — 123. The Bethlehem returnees represent the community associated with David&rsquo;s hometown. After the exile, the connection to ancestral cities was a matter of legal record — it determined land rights in the restoration of the tribal allotments. These &ldquo;men of Bethlehem&rdquo; would have been entitled to the lands historically associated with Bethlehem in the Judahite highlands.</p>",
    "22": "<p>&ldquo;The men of Netophah&rdquo; — 56. Netophah was a town in the Judean highlands south of Jerusalem (Neh 7:26 links it with Bethlehem: 188 combined). Netophathite Levitical singers appear in 1 Chr 9:16 and Neh 12:28, suggesting this town had a particular Levitical character in pre-exilic times.</p>",
    "23": "<p>&ldquo;The men of Anathoth&rdquo; — 128. Anathoth was a Levitical city in Benjamin (Josh 21:18; 1 Chr 6:60) and the hometown of Jeremiah the prophet (Jer 1:1). The returnees from Anathoth would have carried the association with the prophet who had suffered most for predicting the exile and who had also predicted the restoration (Jer 29:10; 31:31-34).</p>",
    "24": "<p>&ldquo;The men of Azmaveth&rdquo; — 42. Azmaveth (&ldquo;death is strong&rdquo;) was a town associated with David&rsquo;s mighty men (2 Sam 23:31; Neh 7:28 calls it &ldquo;Beth-azmaveth,&rdquo; 42). The consistency in numbers here (42 in both lists) indicates stable administrative records for the smaller village communities.</p>",
    "25": "<p>&ldquo;The men of Kiriath-jearim, Chephirah, and Beeroth&rdquo; — 743. These three Gibeonite cities (Josh 9:17) were associated together before the exile and remain grouped in the returnees&rsquo; list. Kiriath-jearim was famous as the resting place of the ark for 20 years before David (1 Sam 6:21-7:2; 1 Chr 13:5-6). Their grouping as a single entry (despite being distinct cities) reflects the administrative unit they had formed before the exile.</p>",
    "26": "<p>&ldquo;The men of Ramah and Geba&rdquo; — 621. Ramah was a prominent Benjaminite city associated with Samuel (1 Sam 7:15-17) and with Jeremiah&rsquo;s lamentation for the exiles (Jer 31:15; &ldquo;a voice is heard in Ramah, lamentation and bitter weeping, Rachel weeping for her children&rdquo;). Geba was a Levitical city (Josh 21:17). Their joint listing reflects their geographic proximity and administrative linkage in the Benjaminite territory.</p>",
    "27": "<p>&ldquo;The men of Michmas&rdquo; — 122. Michmas (Michmash) was a Benjaminite town famous for the battle of Jonathan and his armor-bearer against the Philistines (1 Sam 14). Neh 7:31 agrees at 122. The historical associations of these towns with pre-exilic Israel give the returnees&rsquo; list a quality of national memory — the returning community is re-anchoring itself to the landscape of Israelite history.</p>",
    "28": "<p>&ldquo;The men of Bethel and Ai&rdquo; — 223. Bethel was one of the most significant sites in Israel&rsquo;s history (Jacob&rsquo;s dream, Gen 28; Jeroboam&rsquo;s golden calves, 1 Kgs 12:29). Its association with Ai (destroyed in Joshua&rsquo;s conquest, Josh 8) in the returnees&rsquo; list is historically interesting — both sites had been depopulated or significantly reduced during the monarchy period. Neh 7:32 has 123 — a significant variant for such a historically significant location.</p>",
    "29": "<p>&ldquo;The men of Nebo&rdquo; — 52. There was a Benjaminite Nebo distinct from the Moabite mountain. This is likely the Benjaminite Nebo (Neh 7:33 adds &ldquo;the other Nebo&rdquo; = 52). The small number reflects a minor village that nevertheless had a distinct enough identity to be counted separately in the official registry.</p>",
    "30": "<p>&ldquo;The men of Magbish&rdquo; — 156. Magbish does not appear in the parallel Neh 7 list, which may indicate it was a small settlement that was absorbed into a neighboring administrative unit by the time of Nehemiah&rsquo;s census, or that it was an error for a similar name. This is one of several places where the two lists diverge in ways that cannot be explained by simple scribal variants.</p>",
    "31": "<p>&ldquo;The men of the other Elam&rdquo; — 1,254. This is a second family called Elam (distinct from v7 above, though bearing the same number of 1,254 — a coincidence that may explain why Neh 7 preserves the same dual listing). The qualifier &ldquo;other&rdquo; (<em>ʾaḥer</em>) indicates the author was aware of potential confusion with the first Elam and intentionally distinguished them.</p>",
    "32": "<p>&ldquo;The men of Harim&rdquo; — 320. Harim is also a priestly family (v39 below: 1,017 priests of Harim) — one of the cases where the same name appears in both the lay and priestly lists, probably reflecting separate branches of a family with the same ancestral name. The lay Harim here (320) is distinct from the priestly Harim of v39.</p>",
    "33": "<p>&ldquo;The men of Lod, Hadid, and Ono&rdquo; — 725. These three towns were in the lowland Shephelah west of Jerusalem. Lod (Lydda, modern Lod/Ben Gurion area) and Ono were important trading towns on the coastal plain. Neh 6:2 mentions the &ldquo;plain of Ono&rdquo; as the site of Sanballat&rsquo;s attempted deception of Nehemiah. Their prominence in the returnees&rsquo; list indicates that diaspora Jews from the coastal lowlands also returned, not only from the highland towns.</p>",
    "34": "<p>&ldquo;The men of Jericho&rdquo; — 345. Jericho was one of the oldest continuously occupied sites in the ancient Near East (occupied ca. 9,000 BCE). Its association in Israel&rsquo;s memory is dominated by Joshua&rsquo;s conquest (Josh 2-6). In the Persian period, Jericho was an important administrative town guarding the Jordan Valley route; the returning community&rsquo;s re-establishment of Jericho completes the geographical circuit from Jordan valley to highland to lowland.</p>",
    "35": "<p>&ldquo;The men of Senaah&rdquo; — 3,630. Neh 7:38 has 3,930. Senaah (&ldquo;hated&rdquo; or possibly a place name of uncertain etymology) yields the largest single-entry number in the entire list — larger even than Parosh (2,172). The Senaah builders worked on the Fish Gate section of Jerusalem&rsquo;s wall under Nehemiah (Neh 3:3). Their large number suggests they were a broadly based community rather than a single clan.</p>",
    "36": "<p>The list shifts from lay families to priestly families: &ldquo;The priests: the sons of Jedaiah, of the house of Jeshua&rdquo; — 973. Jedaiah is one of the 24 priestly divisions established by David (1 Chr 24:7). The identification &ldquo;of the house of Jeshua&rdquo; links this priestly family to Jeshua the high priest who leads the return (v2). The 24 Davidic divisions were the organizational framework for priestly rotation in the second temple, as in the first (1 Chr 24).</p>",
    "37": "<p>&ldquo;The sons of Immer&rdquo; — 1,052. Immer is the sixteenth priestly division (1 Chr 24:14) and the family of Pashur the priest who struck Jeremiah and put him in stocks (Jer 20:1). The Immer family was one of the largest priestly families to return. The name appears in the post-exilic community through Neh 3:29; 7:40; 11:13.</p>",
    "38": "<p>&ldquo;The sons of Pashhur&rdquo; — 1,247. Neh 7:41 agrees. Pashhur is a prominent priestly family — they were among those who sealed the covenant with Nehemiah (Neh 10:3). The Pashhur who imprisoned Jeremiah (Jer 20:1) was from this family; their return despite that association with anti-prophetic activity demonstrates the complex and continuous nature of the priestly establishment.</p>",
    "39": "<p>&ldquo;The sons of Harim&rdquo; — 1,017. Harim is the third priestly division (1 Chr 24:8). Together the four returning priestly families (Jedaiah, Immer, Pashhur, Harim) number 4,289 out of the 42,360 total assembly — approximately 10% of the returnees were priests. This very high ratio of priests (compared to the Levitical count of 74 in v40) created the staffing imbalance that would characterize the second temple community: more priests than needed, too few Levites.</p>",
    "40": "<p>&ldquo;The Levites: the sons of Jeshua and Kadmiel, of the sons of Hodaviah&rdquo; — 74. The dramatic contrast between 4,289 priests (vv 36-39) and only 74 Levites reflects a persistent problem in the post-exilic community. Ezra 8:15-20 describes Ezra&rsquo;s desperate recruitment of Levites before his own later return journey — he sent messengers specifically to recruit Levitical families to come. The Levites&rsquo; reluctance to return from Babylon may reflect their relatively comfortable integration into the diaspora, or their sense that the restored temple would not restore their full honor.</p>",
    "41": "<p>&ldquo;The singers, the sons of Asaph&rdquo; — 128. The Asaphite singers are the only musical guild to return (Neh 7:44 agrees at 148 — a modest variant). Asaph was David&rsquo;s chief musician and one of the three guilds established by David (Asaph, Heman, Jeduthun/Ethan, 1 Chr 15:17-19). The absence of Hemanites and Jeduthunites among the returnees leaves Asaph&rsquo;s descendants as the sole musical continuity with the pre-exilic temple tradition. The Asaphite psalms (Pss 50, 73-83) reflect a tradition of lament and covenantal challenge that would have been particularly meaningful to the exile community.</p>",
    "42": "<p>&ldquo;The gatekeepers: the sons of Shallum, Ater, Talmon, Akkub, Hatita, and Shobai&rdquo; — 139. Six families of gatekeepers return together, a smaller number than the singers. The gatekeepers were a specialized Levitical guild responsible for the temple gates — a security and administrative function. David had organized them into 24 divisions (1 Chr 26). Their relatively complete representation (six families) despite small numbers suggests this guild had maintained its organizational structure through the exile.</p>",
    "43": "<p>The Nethinim begin: &ldquo;the sons of Ziha, Hasupha, Tabbaoth&rdquo; — the first three of a long list of Nethinim families (vv 43-54). &ldquo;Nethinim&rdquo; (<em>nĕtînîm</em>) means &ldquo;given ones&rdquo; — people given to temple service. They are probably descendants of the Gibeonites whom Joshua dedicated as &ldquo;hewers of wood and drawers of water&rdquo; for the sanctuary (Josh 9:27) and later groups of war captives donated to temple service. They perform the lowest-level temple maintenance tasks and are listed separately from the Levitical guilds.</p>",
    "44": "<p>&ldquo;The sons of Keros, Siaha, Padon&rdquo; — continuing the Nethinim list. Several Nethinim names are demonstrably non-Israelite: Keros (&ldquo;crooked&rdquo; in Hebrew, but possibly Edomite), Padon (&ldquo;ransom&rdquo; — a common Semitic name), Hagab (v45, &ldquo;locust&rdquo;). This non-Israelite etymology confirms their origin as dedicated temple servants from subjugated peoples rather than Israelite families.</p>",
    "45": "<p>&ldquo;The sons of Lebana, Hagaba, Akkub&rdquo; — Nethinim families continuing. Akkub appears both here (Nethinim) and in v42 (gatekeepers), reflecting either the same name used in two different guilds or textual confusion. The repeated appearance of similar names across the different categories of temple personnel may reflect the Chronicler&rsquo;s organization of distinct groups who had developed overlapping identities through the exile.</p>",
    "46": "<p>&ldquo;The sons of Hagab, Shalmai, Hanan&rdquo; — continuing the Nethinim. The sheer length of the Nethinim list (vv 43-54 = 12 verses, 35+ family groups) compared to the brief entries for Levites (v40, one verse) and singers (v41, one verse) reflects the demographic reality: the lowest-level temple servants were the most numerous category among temple personnel, as in any large institution.</p>",
    "47": "<p>&ldquo;The sons of Giddel, Gahar, Reaiah&rdquo; — three more Nethinim families. Giddel (&ldquo;he has made great&rdquo;) and Gahar (&ldquo;hiding place&rdquo;) are Hebrew names, while Reaiah (&ldquo;YHWH has seen&rdquo;) is a theophoric name suggesting at least some Nethinim families had adopted Yahwistic names by the exile period, reflecting their integration into the covenant community despite their servile status.</p>",
    "48": "<p>&ldquo;The sons of Rezin, Nekoda, Gazzam&rdquo; — Rezin is the name of the Aramean king of Damascus who allied with Pekah of Israel against Ahaz of Judah (Isa 7:1) — a non-Israelite royal name now carried by a temple servant family, illustrating how the Nethinim might include descendants of various subjugated peoples.</p>",
    "49": "<p>&ldquo;The sons of Uzza, Paseah, Besai&rdquo; — continuing the Nethinim. Uzza appears in the ark narrative (2 Sam 6:3-8; 1 Chr 13:7-11) as the man who died touching the ark; whether this Nethinim family traced its origins to that story or simply shared the name is unknown. The rich resonance of many of these names with pre-exilic narratives suggests the post-exilic community preserved these connections as part of its historical memory.</p>",
    "50": "<p>&ldquo;The sons of Asnah, Meunim, Nephisim&rdquo; — Meunim refers to the Meunites, a people from the region of Maon south of Edom, frequently mentioned as enemies of Israel in Chronicles (2 Chr 20:1; 26:7). Their descendants appear here as dedicated temple servants — illustrating how war captives from Israel&rsquo;s border conflicts became integrated into the temple service over generations, a phenomenon also seen in the ancient Near East where captured peoples served the victors&rsquo; temples.</p>",
    "51": "<p>&ldquo;The sons of Bakbuk, Hakupha, Harhur&rdquo; — three more Nethinim families with non-Hebrew names that suggest foreign origins. Hakupha may be Egyptian in origin. The linguistic variety of Nethinim names across vv 43-54 reflects the diverse ethnic origins of people pressed into temple service through Israel&rsquo;s military history.</p>",
    "52": "<p>&ldquo;The sons of Bazluth, Mehida, Harsha&rdquo; — continuing the Nethinim. By this point in the list, the reader is meant to perceive the sheer scope of the temple service community: even the lowest-ranked temple servants constitute a large and diversified community with its own internal organization and family identity.</p>",
    "53": "<p>&ldquo;The sons of Barkos, Sisera, Temah&rdquo; — Sisera is the name of the Canaanite general whom Jael killed (Judg 4:17-22). The presence of Sisera as a Nethinim family name confirms that descendants of Israel&rsquo;s historical enemies had been incorporated into the lowest rungs of temple service — a remarkable continuity spanning the pre-monarchic period through the exile to the restoration.</p>",
    "54": "<p>&ldquo;The sons of Neziah, Hatipha&rdquo; — the final Nethinim families before &ldquo;the sons of Solomon&rsquo;s servants&rdquo; in v55. These two families complete the Nethinim list. Nehemiah 7:56 agrees. The Nethinim community remained distinct as a recognized group in the post-exilic period, appearing in Ezra 8:17-20, where Ezra specifically requests their inclusion in the return journey.</p>",
    "55": "<p>&ldquo;The sons of Solomon&rsquo;s servants&rdquo; begin: Sotai, Sophereth, Peruda. &ldquo;Solomon&rsquo;s servants&rdquo; (<em>ʿaḇdê šelōmōh</em>) are a group parallel to the Nethinim but distinguished from them — probably descendants of the Canaanite labor force Solomon conscripted for his building projects (1 Kgs 9:20-21; 2 Chr 8:7-8). They are lower in status than even the Nethinim; their separate listing preserves the memory of their distinct origins in Solomonic royal service.</p>",
    "56": "<p>&ldquo;The sons of Jaala, Darkon, Giddel&rdquo; — Solomon&rsquo;s servants continuing. Jaala and Darkon appear in Neh 7:58-59. The name Giddel appears both here (v56) and in the Nethinim list (v47), reflecting the overlapping onomastic (naming) traditions of these lower-status temple-service communities.</p>",
    "57": "<p>&ldquo;The sons of Shephatiah, Hattil, Pochereth-hazzebaim, and Ami&rdquo; — the final group of Solomon&rsquo;s servants. Pochereth-hazzebaim (&ldquo;binding of the gazelles&rdquo;) is a striking compound name, possibly indicating a family associated with royal hunting or animal management in the Solomonic court. Neh 7:59 has &ldquo;Amon&rdquo; for &ldquo;Ami.&rdquo;</p>",
    "58": "<p>Total: all the Nethinim and sons of Solomon&rsquo;s servants were 392. Together they form a substantial portion of the returning community and will provide the essential maintenance workforce for the new temple. Their enumeration in the official registry gives them legal standing as part of the restored covenant community — their servile origins do not exclude them from the census that defines membership in the people of God.</p>",
    "59": "<p>Those who could not prove their Israelite ancestry: from Tel-melah, Tel-harsha, Cherub, Addan, and Immer. These were towns in Babylonia (identified by the prefix &ldquo;tel,&rdquo; ruin-mound, indicating they were established settlements in Mesopotamia). People from these places had been part of the Jewish exile community but lacked genealogical records proving their tribal lineage. The concern for lineage reflects the post-exilic community&rsquo;s emphasis on verifiable descent from pre-exilic Israel as the criterion for full membership.</p>",
    "60": "<p>&ldquo;The sons of Delaiah, Tobiah, and Nekoda&rdquo; — 652 persons who could not verify their ancestry. These 652 remain in limbo: they are counted in the census but excluded from the priestly ranks pending verification. The Tobiah mentioned here is not the Ammonite adversary of Nehemiah; the name was common. The concern for genealogical purity in the returned community is a response to the exile&rsquo;s disruption of the social structures that had maintained family records.</p>",
    "61": "<p>The priestly families who cannot prove their lineage: sons of Habaiah, Hakkoz, and Barzillai. The case of Barzillai is especially poignant — a priestly family that had taken its identity from Barzillai the Gileadite (2 Sam 17:27-29; 19:31-38) by intermarriage and then adopted the family name, thereby losing its priestly genealogical record. The conflation of family identity through marriage reflects the social disruptions of the pre-exilic and exilic periods.</p>",
    "62": "<p>&ldquo;These sought their registration among those enrolled in the genealogies, but it was not found there; so they were excluded from the priesthood as unclean (<em>yĕgōʾălû</em>).&rdquo; The technical term &ldquo;as unclean&rdquo; (&ldquo;polluted,&rdquo; <em>gāʾal</em>) does not mean they were ritually impure but that their priestly status was suspended pending verification. The priestly genealogies were the key administrative record for determining who could serve at the altar and eat from the priestly portions. Their absence from the record creates a crisis of identity that requires prophetic resolution.</p>",
    "63": "<p>&ldquo;The governor (<em>hattirshāthā</em>) told them that they were not to partake of the most holy food until there should be a priest to consult Urim and Thummim.&rdquo; The Tirshatha (a Persian title for governor, used for Zerubbabel here and Nehemiah in Neh 8:9; 10:1) cannot resolve the genealogical question by administrative fiat. The solution must await a priest who can use the Urim and Thummim — the sacred divination lots used by the pre-exilic high priest to determine YHWH&rsquo;s decision in disputed cases (Exod 28:30; Num 27:21). The implicit acknowledgment is that no functioning Urim and Thummim are available in the restoration community — it awaits eschatological resolution.</p>",
    "64": "<p>&ldquo;The whole assembly together was 42,360.&rdquo; This is the same number as in Neh 7:66. The figure is notable because it is larger than the sum of all individual entries (which totals approximately 29,818 in Ezra 2 and 31,089 in Neh 7). The excess 12,542 or so persons must represent women, children, non-Judahites, or people from other tribal backgrounds not listed by the male-headed family groups. The Nehemiah parallel makes the same total-vs-sum discrepancy, confirming it is present in the original source document rather than a copying error.</p>",
    "65": "<p>&ldquo;Besides their male and female servants, of whom there were 7,337.&rdquo; The presence of servants in the returnees&rsquo; roster further explains the population gap — the servants are not counted in the family tallies but are enumerated separately. &ldquo;They also had 200 male and female singers&rdquo; — professional secular singers (distinct from the temple singers of v41), comparable to the musicians who accompanied royal processions and banquets in the ancient Near East. Their presence indicates that the return was not a poverty migration but a movement that retained some of the cultural accoutrements of the pre-exilic Judahite elite.</p>",
    "66": "<p>&ldquo;Their horses were 736, their mules 245&rdquo; — the livestock inventory begins. Horses in the ancient Near East were primarily military and prestige animals (ordinary people used donkeys for transportation and agriculture). The presence of 736 horses suggests the returning community included people of significant social standing who traveled in the manner of the Babylonian elite.</p>",
    "67": "<p>&ldquo;Their camels 435, their donkeys 6,720.&rdquo; Donkeys were the primary work animal of the ancient Levant and their large number (6,720) reflects the predominantly agricultural and commercial character of the return. Camels were used for long-distance trade and desert travel; their presence (435) indicates some returnees were engaged in the caravan trade network that connected Babylonia with Judah via the Aramean territories.</p>",
    "68": "<p>&ldquo;Some of the heads of fathers&rsquo; houses, when they came to the house of YHWH which is in Jerusalem, made freewill offerings (<em>hitnaḏḏĕḇû</em>) for the house of God.&rdquo; The verb <em>nāḏaḇ</em> (give freely, volunteer) is the characteristic term for the voluntary spirit that motivated the tabernacle offerings (Exod 35:21-29; 36:2-7). The leaders&rsquo; immediate giving upon arrival — before any organizational structure is in place — signals the priority of temple rebuilding and the voluntary spirit that the Chronicler considers essential to proper worship. Giving is the first act of the returned community at the temple site.</p>",
    "69": "<p>&ldquo;According to their ability they gave to the treasury of the work 61,000 darics of gold, 5,000 minas of silver, and 100 priests&rsquo; garments.&rdquo; The Daric was a Persian gold coin minted under Darius I (522-486 BCE) — its appearance in a Cyrus-era return suggests either anachronism or (more likely) that the list was edited in its final form under Darius. 61,000 darics represented an enormous sum for a returning exile community; the inclusion of 100 priestly garments alongside monetary gifts indicates that practical vestments for temple service were immediately prioritized, not just the building materials.</p>",
    "70": "<p>&ldquo;The priests and Levites, and some of the people lived in Jerusalem and its vicinity; and the singers, gatekeepers, and the temple servants lived in their towns, and all Israel in their towns.&rdquo; The administrative settlement narrative: the census lists define who settles where. Jerusalem receives the essential temple personnel (priests, Levites, some laity); the outlying towns receive the singers, gatekeepers, Nethinim, and the rest of the lay population. This settlement pattern reflects the pre-exilic pattern where the Levitical cities housed temple personnel who commuted to Jerusalem for their assigned service weeks.</p>"
  },
  "3": {
    "1": "<p>The seventh month (<em>haššĕḇîʿî</em>) — Tishri, September-October — was the most sacred month in the Israelite religious calendar: it contained the Feast of Trumpets (Num 29:1-6), the Day of Atonement (Lev 16; Num 29:7-11), and the Feast of Tabernacles (Lev 23:34-43; Num 29:12-38). The convergence of the community in Jerusalem in this month reflects deliberate religious calendaring: the returnees gather for the high holy days as soon as the community is settled. The phrase &ldquo;as one man&rdquo; (<em>kĕʾîš ʾeḥāḏ</em>) is used elsewhere for the unified assembly of Israel (Judg 20:1; 1 Sam 11:7) — a phrase connoting both unity and totality.</p>",
    "2": "<p>&ldquo;Then Jeshua the son of Jozadak, with his fellow priests, and Zerubbabel the son of Shealtiel with his kinsmen, arose and built the altar of the God of Israel.&rdquo; The first act of the restored community is the rebuilding of the altar — before the city walls, before the temple building, before any other infrastructure. This priority follows a principle reflected in Ezekiel&rsquo;s restoration vision (Ezek 40-48) and in the logic of the sacrificial system: the altar enables the offerings that establish the covenant relationship; the building that houses it is secondary. The Mosaic precedent: the altar at the base of Sinai preceded the tabernacle (Exod 24:4; cf. Exod 40).</p>",
    "3": "<p>&ldquo;They set the altar in its place... though fear was upon them because of the peoples of the lands.&rdquo; The phrase &ldquo;fear of the peoples of the lands&rdquo; (<em>bĕʾêmāh ʿālêhem mēʿammê hāʾărāṣôt</em>) indicates the security threat from the surrounding non-Jewish population. The decision to establish the altar despite this fear follows the pattern of the wilderness generation: Israel continued its worship in the desert despite external threat. The altar&rsquo;s divine protection was more reliable than any human fortification — the covenant relationship maintained through sacrifice was the community&rsquo;s primary defense.</p>",
    "4": "<p>&ldquo;They kept the Feast of Booths (<em>sukkôt</em>) as prescribed, and offered the daily burnt offerings by number according to the rule, as each day required.&rdquo; The Feast of Tabernacles was the first festival celebrated in the restored community. Its choice is theologically apt: Tabernacles commemorated the wilderness wandering (Lev 23:42-43), and the returning exile community was again in a vulnerable, tent-dwelling situation awaiting the building of permanent structures. The prescription &ldquo;as each day required&rdquo; (<em>kidbar yôm bĕyômô</em>) emphasizes strict Torah compliance — the restored community does not innovate but adheres to Mosaic legislation.</p>",
    "5": "<p>&ldquo;And after that, the continual burnt offerings (<em>ʿōlat hattāmîḏ</em>), the offerings at the new moon and at all the appointed feasts of YHWH.&rdquo; The <em>ʿōlat hattāmîd</em> — the twice-daily burnt offering (morning and evening lamb, Exod 29:38-42; Num 28:3-8) — was the heartbeat of the temple&rsquo;s ritual life. The restoration of the <em>tāmîḏ</em> meant that YHWH&rsquo;s worship was functioning again on a continuous, calendrical basis. The list (Tabernacles → new moons → appointed feasts → freewill offerings) progresses from the specific festival just celebrated to the full annual cycle, signaling the community&rsquo;s intent to observe the entire liturgical calendar.</p>",
    "6": "<p>&ldquo;From the first day of the seventh month they began to offer burnt offerings to YHWH, but the foundation of the temple of YHWH had not yet been laid.&rdquo; The editorial note is significant: sacrifice precedes construction. The community does not wait for the temple building to be complete before restoring worship. This precedent — worship at an altar before any structure — appears earlier in Israel&rsquo;s history (the patriarchal altars of Gen 12:7-8; 13:18 etc.) and provides theological precedent for the NT principle that the community of worshipers is the temple rather than the building (1 Cor 3:16).</p>",
    "7": "<p>&ldquo;They gave money to the masons and the carpenters, and food, drink, and oil to the Sidonians and Tyrians to bring cedar trees from Lebanon.&rdquo; The Solomonic building pattern is deliberately replicated: Solomon also used Tyrian craftsmen and Lebanese cedar (1 Kgs 5:1-12; 2 Chr 2:1-16). The imitation of Solomon&rsquo;s temple construction method signals the second temple&rsquo;s intention to recreate the glory of the first. The involvement of Sidonians and Tyrians also reflects the continued role of Phoenician craftsmen as the Mediterranean&rsquo;s premier woodworkers and architects throughout the Iron Age and Persian period.</p>",
    "8": "<p>&ldquo;In the second year of their coming to the house of God at Jerusalem, in the second month, Zerubbabel the son of Shealtiel and Jeshua the son of Jozadak made a beginning.&rdquo; The second year, second month — the exact same timing as Solomon&rsquo;s temple construction (1 Kgs 6:1: &ldquo;in the four hundred and eightieth year... in the second month&rdquo;; 2 Chr 3:2). The Levites &ldquo;from twenty years old and upward&rdquo; supervise the work — a departure from the Mosaic age of 30 for Levitical service (Num 4:3), justified by the urgent need for temple workers and following the precedent of 1 Chr 23:24-27 where David lowered the age to 20.</p>",
    "9": "<p>&ldquo;Jeshua with his sons and kinsmen, and Kadmiel and his sons, the sons of Judah, stood together to supervise the workmen.&rdquo; The Levitical supervisors are named: two main families (Jeshua&rsquo;s kin and Kadmiel&rsquo;s kin) plus &ldquo;the sons of Henadad, with their sons and kinsmen, the Levites&rdquo; (Neh 3:18, 24 confirm Henadad&rsquo;s family as prominent Levitical builders). The Levitical oversight of construction follows the pattern established for the tabernacle (Num 4:5-33) and for temple construction (1 Chr 23:4).</p>",
    "10": "<p>&ldquo;When the builders laid the foundation of the temple of YHWH, the priests in their vestments came forward with trumpets, and the Levites, the sons of Asaph, with cymbals, to praise YHWH.&rdquo; The foundation-laying ceremony follows the Davidic music tradition: priests with silver trumpets (Num 10:8) and Asaphite Levites with cymbals — the same combination used when David brought the ark to Jerusalem (1 Chr 15:24, 28) and at Solomon&rsquo;s temple dedication (2 Chr 5:12-13). Music marks the transition from profane space to sacred space; the ceremony transforms a building site into a holy precinct.</p>",
    "11": "<p>&ldquo;They sang responsively, praising and giving thanks to YHWH, &lsquo;For he is good, for his steadfast love (<em>kî lĕʿōlām ḥasĕdô</em>) endures forever toward Israel.&rsquo;&rdquo; The refrain is the liturgical formula of Ps 136 and the temple dedication (2 Chr 5:13; 7:3) — the same words that filled the first temple with the Shekinah cloud. The singing of this refrain at the second temple&rsquo;s foundation is a deliberate act of covenant recollection: YHWH&rsquo;s steadfast love that had sustained Israel through the Exodus now sustains them through the return from exile. The community hears its own story in the refrain&rsquo;s eternal present tense (&ldquo;endures forever&rdquo;).</p>",
    "12": "<p>&ldquo;But many of the priests and Levites and heads of fathers&rsquo; houses, old men who had seen the first house, wept with a loud voice.&rdquo; The temple had been destroyed in 586 BCE; for those now approximately 586 + 538 = over 70 years of age (born before the destruction), or those who had witnessed it as children, the second temple&rsquo;s modest foundation was a reminder of what had been lost. Haggai 2:3 directly addresses these weepers: &ldquo;Who is left among you who saw this house in its former glory? How do you see it now? Is it not as nothing in your eyes?&rdquo; The prophetic response will be that the second temple&rsquo;s &ldquo;latter glory shall be greater than the former&rdquo; (Hag 2:9).</p>",
    "13": "<p>&ldquo;And the people could not distinguish the sound of the joyful shout from the sound of the people&rsquo;s weeping, for the people shouted with a great shout, and the sound was heard far away.&rdquo; The mixed response — joy from those celebrating restoration, grief from those remembering what was lost — defines the eschatological tension of the entire post-exilic period. The restoration is real but incomplete; the promise has been partially fulfilled. This ambiguity drives the prophetic ministry of Haggai and Zechariah, who acknowledge the grief while insisting on the coming greater glory. The mixed sound heard &ldquo;far away&rdquo; signals to the surrounding peoples that something significant has occurred in Jerusalem.</p>"
  }
}

def main():
    existing = load_comm('mkt-context', 'ezra')
    before = sum(len(v) for v in existing.values())
    merge_comm(existing, EZRA_CONTEXT_1_3)
    after = sum(len(v) for v in existing.values())
    save_comm('mkt-context', 'ezra', existing)
    print(f'ezra mkt-context ch 1-3: wrote {after - before} verses')

if __name__ == '__main__':
    main()
